Claimant Count and Universal Credit in Trafford

Claimant Count in Trafford

The Claimant Count indicates the number of people claiming benefits principally for the reason of being unemployed. The Claimant Count in January 2022 was 46.1% higher than in January 2020. The rate of claimants to residents aged 16 to 64 reached 3.4% in January 2022 representing an increment of 1.1% from January 2020. The number of claimants has been decreasing from April 2021.

Change in the Claimant Count for Trafford

The Trafford ward with the largest share of claims in January 2022 was Clifford with 11.8% of all claimants within Trafford. All the wards have less claims in January 2022 compared to January 2021. Clifford has the largest reduction in number of claims with -280 followed by Bucklow-St Martins (-200), Gorse Hill (-190) and Longford (-185).

Change in the Claimant Count for Trafford's wards

The wards with higher claimant rate in January 2022 were Clifford and Bucklow-St Martins with 6.8% and 6.6% respectively. The wards where the claimant rate has decreased more from January 2021 to January 2022 are Bucklow-St Martins and Clifford with a decrease in rate of -3.2% and -3.2% respectively followed by Gorse Hill and Longford with -2.3%.

In Trafford from January 2021 to January 2022 almost all age bands have reduced their claimant count. When considering the reduction of claims the age band 18-24 years had the largest reduction with -620 less claims.

Change in the Claimant Count by age bands in Trafford
Change in the Claimant Count by broad age bands in Trafford

At the start of 2020 the age band 25-34 already had the highest number of claims, however after the effects of the Covid-19 pandemic which started in March 2020 this figure increased more sharply compared to the other age bands. The claimant rate as a proportion of Trafford’s population within each age band shows a higher increase in the age bands of 16-24 and 25-34 compared to the others. The rate and count is decreasing for all age bands particularly for the the age bands of 16-24 and 25-34.

Almost half of Trafford’s claimants are residents of five of the 21 wards. Almost half of the claimants are under 34 years.

Claimant Count for Trafford's wards by age band

Universal Credit claims in Trafford

The Universal Credit claims in Trafford have increased 76.1% from January 2020 to January 2022. The rate of claims as a proportion of people age 16 to 64 increased form 6.1% to 10.8%.

Change in the Universal Credit claims for Trafford

The Trafford MSOA with the largest share of claims in January 2022 was Old Trafford with 11.7% of all Universal Credit claims in Trafford. All the MSOAs have less claims in January 2022 compared to January 2021. The MSOA with more reduction in percentage change from January 2021 to January 2022 was Timperley South with -34% change. The MSOAs with the least reduction in claims from January 2021 to January 2022 were Sale North with -18 and West Timperley with -20. The MSOAs with more reduction in claims when comparing January 2021 to January 2022 are Broadheath & Firsway (-125), Old Trafford (-115) and Stretford East (-107).

Change in the Universal Credit claims for Trafford's MSOAs

The MSOAs with higher rates of Universal Credit claims in January 2022 were Partington with 26.3% and Old Trafford with 23.1%. The MSOAs where the rate of Universal Credit claims has decrease less from January 2021 to January 2022 were Sale North with -0.3%, Partington with -0.4% and West Timperley with -0.4%.

In Trafford from January 2021 to January 2022 the Over 65 age bands have the largest increment in the number of Universal Credit claims with 27%. When considering the number of additional claims from January 2021 to January 2022 the 5-year age band 60-65 years had the highest with 73 more claims. The age bands 20-24 and 25-29 have the largest decrease in number of Universal Credit claims.

Change in the Universal Credit claims by age band for Trafford

Following the start of the Covid-19 pandemic in March 2020 the number of claims for all ages rose dramatically from pre-pandemic levels at a similar proportion for all age bands with the age band 16-24 rising faster in May 2020. At the start of 2020 the age band 25-34 had the highest number of claims and also the highest rate maintaining that position after the rise from Mar 2020. All the age bands are decreasing or maintaining their levels particularly the age bands 16-24 and 25-34 that are decreasing more rapidly on rate and number of claims from April 2021.

The Conditionality regimen for entitlement to Universal Credit is associated to work-related things that claimants will have to do to maintain elegibility. In Trafford the largest proportion of Universal Credit claims are in the “Searching for Work” category however there is also a significant proportion of claims under “No work requirements”.
